ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=drv,y=hwy))+geom_point()

now after this we are going to changw the aesthetic properties of the data points, these properties could be the shape size and colour of the data point , all these can be changed inthe aesthetic part of the ggplot

ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=displ,y=hwy,color=class))+geom_point()

in above we had used the color aesthtic to make the graph but we can use the size aesthetic too to make it a greart thing but in this scinario its not a great idea, infact its a bad one as we know that for this case its bbatter that all are categorical

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

as its clear that using shape aesthetic in this case is not that great, now we are going to make thing more clear by using the alpha aesthtic use for transparency and shape aesthetic

# Left
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))

# Right
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7.
## Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

so here is limitation of using the shape aesthetic it can max distinguish only 6 aes

and also behind the scene the aes function is mapping the x and y given to it and then create a visual layer add legends to it and create axis as per the data points we can manully do this using

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "blue")

we can also use stroke aesthetic too so that any conditional operation on aesthetic color give ys a bollean plot showing which point obey that condition and which are nor t

ggplot(data=mpg)+geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy,color=(displ<5) ))

shape aesthetic can be used to change the border width

facet_wrap()

can be used to make subplot based on some categorical value, sothat we can individual or cattegoricaly study these all

ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+geom_point()+facet_wrap(~class,nrow = 2)

here we are being able to see the plot based on each category if we want to make grph on basis of combination of two then we use facet_grid() both these have only few categorn so easy to view

ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+geom_point()+facet_grid(drv~cyl)

lets try examples too

ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=displ))+geom_histogram()+facet_grid(hwy~class)

no this plot is hactic rather than any other thing so keep in mind not o use continious var for facet_grid and is use make bin size large or the data rane must be low

we can plot same x and y with different geom function too and like for pointplot and smooth these are ploteed on same data but from different

ggplot(data=mpg)+geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy,color=(displ<5) ))

ggplot(data=mpg)+geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy ))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

ggplot(data = mpg)+geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

so by adding layer we can make graphs containg differnt geom object but its also came up of redundancy that if we wanrt to change only 1 legend it must be changed in bot

solution>

try to gve mapping to at once to ggplot and after that change the filters or the relevant layers

####the redundant way
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

######################################################### non redundant way
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'
